Source: {'Header 1': 'ONE ZERO Bank Guide on Card Usage and Services', 'Header 2': 'Ordering a card', 'Header 3': 'Replacing Damaged Card', 'source': 'cards.md'}
Content: If your card from Isracard is damaged, log in to your account and go to the Cards page. Select the option to cancel the damaged card and order a new one. The damaged card will remain active until the new one is received and activated. If you encounter any issues during the replacement process, contact Isracard's customer support for assistance.

Source: {'Header 1': 'ONE ZERO Bank Guide on Card Usage and Services', 'Header 2': 'Ordering a card', 'Header 3': 'Replacing a card', 'source': 'cards.md'}
Content: If your credit card or debit card from Isracard is lost, stolen or damaged, you can request a replacement. Log in to your Isracard account and navigate to the Cards page. Select the option to cancel the old card and order a new one. Depending on your subscription plan, there might be a fee for immediate replacement. The new card will be delivered to your address within a specific time frame. Remember to activate the new card as soon as you receive it to ensure uninterrupted usage. If your credit card has been blocked, you can request a debit card instead. To order a new debit card, access the cards page in the application, choose to order a new card, and there you will have the option of issuing a new debit card if you do not already have one in your account.
If you want to replace a card you received, there is a cost of 10 ILS for a regular order and 40 ILS for an immediate issuance for customers on the ZERO subscription plan. Customers on the ONE subscription plan and ONE PLUS subscription plan do not have to pay this fee as part of the expanded fee exemption subscription plan. To order a card, go to the Cards page, tap on Order and then choose to order a New Card. You can order a replacement card from the [cards page](https://app.tfd-bank.com/portfolio/cards). For further assistance, contact a [private banker](/actions/attach_agent).

Source: {'Header 1': 'ONE ZERO Bank Guide on Card Usage and Services', 'Header 2': 'Connecting Cards to online payment sites', 'Header 3': 'Updating Contact Information', 'source': 'cards.md'}
Content: Customers can update their phone number and email address associated with the card by logging into the respective platforms or apps and accessing the profile or settings sections. Contacting a private banker is an option for customers who prefer assistance with updating contact information or other card-related tasks with Isracard. You can contact a [private banker](/actions/attach_agent).

Source: {'Header 1': 'ONE ZERO Bank Guide on Card Usage and Services', 'Header 2': 'Cash Withdrawals', 'Header 3': 'Depositing cash', 'source': 'cards.md'}
Content: At this time, cash deposits are still not possible to ONE ZERO Bank accounts. However, the bank is working on making cash deposits possible and will update all customers as soon as it becomes possible. You can transfer money into your account from an account in another bank and deposit cheques.

Source: {'Header 1': 'ONE ZERO Bank Guide on Card Usage and Services', 'Header 2': 'Cash Withdrawals', 'Header 3': 'Cash withdrawal fees from ATMs in Israel using ONE ZERO credit card or debit card', 'source': 'cards.md'}
Content: Cash withdrawal from an ATM belonging to any bank in Israel is free of withdrawal fees. Private ATMs companies charge their own fees, therefore, we recommend that you withdraw cash from bank-run ATMs connected to a branch in order to avoid these fees. It is not possible to withdraw money without a card. If you withdrew cash from an ATM with operating or third-party fees, then the fee is from the ATM operator, not ONE ZERO bank.

Source: {'Header 1': 'ONE ZERO Bank Guide on Card Usage and Services', 'Header 2': 'Cash Withdrawals', 'Header 3': 'Double charge by ATM', 'source': 'cards.md'}
Content: If you tried to make a withdrawal and were charged twice, or received a different amount than you requested to withdraw And you did not receive the money, the ATM system performs an automatic count at the end of the business day, and if there is a discrepancy, it does not charge the account. If 3 business days have passed, and the charge is still deducted from your account, and no automatic credit has been received, notify a [private banker](/actions/attach_agent) for further assistance regarding the request while specifying where the withdrawal was made and for what amount.

Source: {'Header 1': 'ONE ZERO Bank Guide on Card Usage and Services', 'Header 2': 'Cash Withdrawals', 'Header 3': 'Handling Cash Withdrawal Failures', 'source': 'cards.md'}
Content: Handling failures in ATM withdrawals differs between ATMs in Israel and those abroad:
* Failures in withdrawals from ATMs in Israel – If you attempted to withdraw cash from an ATM in Israel and no cash was dispensed, but you still see a charge on your account, it is generally recommended to wait three business days for the funds to be credited back. If, after three business days, you have not received a refund, you can contact a [private banker](/actions/attach_agent) for further assistance. Please specify the ATM location and the withdrawal amount. If you used a debit card, the withdrawal may not be finalized and could appear as a pending transaction. In this case, you should wait 24 hours to ensure that the pending charge is removed.
* Failures in withdrawals from ATMs abroad – If you attempted to withdraw cash from an ATM abroad and the transaction failed, please contact [Isracard's customer service](https://digital.isracard.co.il/Abroad/lobby/Abroad/CustomerService/) for assistance.

Source: {'Header 1': 'ONE ZERO Bank Guide on Card Usage and Services', 'Header 2': 'Cash Withdrawals', 'Header 3': 'Cash Withdrawals limit using ONE ZERO Debit Card', 'source': 'cards.md'}
Content: The daily limit for cash withdrawal from ATM with ONE ZERO bank's Debit Card is different between withdrawals abroad and withdrawals inside Israel's borders:
* Withdrawal from ATM inside Israel borders with Debit Card - You can make purchases of up to 3,000 ILS per single transaction and to withdraws up to 5,000 ILS per day from any ATM inside Israel borders. For purchases exceeding 3,000 ILS on the debit card, therefore you will have to ask the merchant to split the bill into two payments.
* Withdrawal from ATM abroad with a Debit Card - You can withdraw up to 3,000 ILS per day from ATMs abroad, as long as there is remaining balance in your account.

